    "(2) Token Frequency ↔ Learning Signal: In a neural network, the magnitude of the gradient |∇E t i,j | at each token occurrence can be interpreted as the strength of the learning signal, i.e., how much the token contributes to updating the model's parameters.",
    "ϕ(E i) aggregates these gradients and reflects the cumulative learning signal for token i over all its occurrences.",
    "We hypothesize that this learning signal is proportional to the token's information content.",
    "In other words, for some constant c > 0, we expect that:",
    "This proportionality implies that as the frequency f i increases, the aggregated gradient magnitude ϕ(E i) decreases."
